  "diary": "Woke to that soft grey drizzle—checked on the basil and thyme up on the roof, they're drinking it in. Coffee tasted better than usual today, maybe because I spent an extra few minutes with my foraging notes before heading out. The commute was a mess with the bridge closure, but I know these streets well enough. Got to Shiro's early and threw myself into the lunch prep—new kid on staff needed some hand-holding with the Burgundies, which I didn't mind. The day felt unhurried until dinner service kicked in around five. Paired a beautiful Cabernet with someone's ribeye, watched them light up at the first sip. That never gets old. Drove home through the rain, and by the time I got to Beacon Hill, I was already thinking about Rattlesnake Lake. Spread out my maps for a bit, stretched out the stiffness. There's something about a grey day that makes you want to plan something green.",
  "thought_process": "The weather kept me grounded today—literally checking on my garden before work set a contemplative tone I carried through service. The bridge closure could've rattled me, but I've learned that frustration doesn't help anyone, so I just took the long way. Training the new staff felt purposeful; I remember being that uncertain once. During the afternoon lull, I shifted into planning mode because the rain reminded me I should capitalize on the season for foraging. By dinner service, I was back in my element—reading guests, reading wines. The day didn't demand much of me emotionally, which meant I could be fully present with the work itself. That's when I do my best.",
